## <a name='new'></a> Create a New Quota Plan for an Org

<p class="note"><strong>Note:</strong> The org manager sets and manages quotas. For more information, see <a href="../concepts/roles.html">Orgs, Spaces, Roles, and Permissions</a>.</p>

You must set an org quota. You can create a new quota plan for org with [`cf create-quota`](#create-quota).
<% end %>


### <a name='create-quota'></a> Use cf create-org-quota

In a terminal window, run the following command. Replace the placeholder attributes with the values for this quota plan:

Note: `create-quota` is an alias for `create-org-quota`.

```
cf create-quota QUOTA [-m TOTAL-MEMORY] [-i INSTANCE-MEMORY] [-l LOG_RATE] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICE-INSTANCES] [--allow-paid-service-plans]
```

This command accepts the following flags:

* `-m`: Total amount of memory
* `-i`: Maximum amount of memory an application instance can have (`-1` represents an unlimited amount)
* `-l`: Total amount of logs allowed per second
* `-r`: Total number of routes
* `-s`: Total number of service instances
* `-allow-paid-service-plans`: Can provision instances of paid service plans

Example:

<pre class='terminal'>
$ cf create-quota small -m 1024M -i 1024M -l 2k -r 10 -s 10 --allow-paid-service-plans
</pre>


## <a name='modify'></a> Modify an Existing Quota Plan for an Org

<% if vars.platform_code == 'CF' %>

You can modify an existing quota plan for an org in one of two ways:

* Directly modify the <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> deployment manifest before deploying.
* Use `cf update-quota` (or its alias `cf update-org-quota`) after deploying.

### <a name='modify-manifest'></a> Modify the Manifest

To modify the <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> deployment manifest:

1. Open the deployment YAML manifest file in a text editor.

1. Search for `quota_definitions`.

1. Modify the value of the attribute.

1. Save and close the deployment manifest.

<% end %>

### <a name='update-quota'></a> Use cf update-org-quota

1. Run `cf quotas` to find the names of all quota definitions available to your org. Record the name of the 
quota plan to be modified.

Note: `quotas` is an alias for `org-quotas`.

<pre class='terminal'>
$ cf quotas
Getting org quotas as admin...

name      total memory   instance memory   routes   service instances   paid service plans   app instances   route ports   log volume per second
default   100G           unlimited         1000     unlimited           allowed              unlimited       100           unlimited
free      0              unlimited         1000     0                   disallowed           unlimited       0             4K
paid      10M            unlimited         1000     unlimited           allowed              unlimited       0             unlimited
small     1G             1G                10       10                  allowed              unlimited       0             2K
trial     2G             1G                1000     0                   disallowed           unlimited       0             1K
</pre>

1. Run the following command, replacing QUOTA with the name of your quota:

Note: `update-quota` is an alias for `update-org-quota`.

```
cf update-quota QUOTA [-i INSTANCE-MEMORY] [-m MEMORY] [-l LOG_RATE] [-n NEW-NAME] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICE-INSTANCES] [--allow-paid-service-plans | --disallow-paid-service-plans]
```

<br><br>
    This command accepts the following flags:
    * `-i`: Maximum amount of memory an application instance can have (`-1` represents an unlimited amount)
    * `-m`: Total amount of memory a space can have
    * `-l`: Total amount of logs allowed per second
    * `-n`: New name
    * `-r`: Total number of routes
    * `-s`: Total number of service instances
    * `--allow-paid-service-plans`: Can provision instances of paid service plans
    * `--disallow-paid-service-plans`: Can not provision instances of paid service plans

      Example:
      <pre class='terminal'> $ cf update-quota small -i 2048M -m 4096M -l 8K -n medium -r 20 -s 20 --allow-paid-service-plans</pre>

## <a name='set-org-quota'></a> Assigning a quota to an organization

To assign a quota to an organization, run the following command. Replace the placeholder attributes with the values for this quota plan:

```
cf set-org-quota ORG QUOTA
```

Example:

<pre class='terminal'>
$ cf set-org-quota anOrg small
</pre>


## <a name='space'></a> Create and Modify Quota Plans for a Space

For each org, Org Managers create and modify quota plans for spaces in the org. If an Org Manager allocates a space quota, <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> verifies that resources do not exceed the allocated space limit. For example, when a Space Developer deploys an app, <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> first checks the memory allocation at the space level, then at the org level.

Perform the following procedures to create and modify quota plans for individual spaces within an org.

### <a name='new-space'></a> Create a New Quota Plan for a Space

In a terminal window, run the following command to create a quota for a space. Replace the placeholder attributes with the values for this quota plan:

```
cf create-space-quota QUOTA [-i INSTANCE-MEMORY] [-m MEMORY] [-l LOG_RATE] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICE-INSTANCES] [--allow-paid-service-plans]
```

Example:

<pre class='terminal'>
$ cf create-space-quota big -i 1024M -m 4096M -l 16K -r 20 -s 20 --allow-paid-service-plans
</pre>

### <a name='modify-space'></a> Modify a Quota Plan for a Space

Run `cf space-quotas` to find the names of all space quota available to your org. Record the name of the quota plan to be modified.

<pre class='terminal'>
$ cf space-quotas
Getting space quotas for org o as admin...

name    total memory   instance memory   routes   service instances   paid service plans   app instances   route ports   log volume per second
big     4G             1G                20       20                  allowed              unlimited       0             16K
trial   2G             1G                20       20                  allowed              unlimited       0             2K
</pre>

To modify that quota, use the `update-space-quota` command. Replace the placeholder attributes with the values for this quota plan.

```
cf update-space-quota SPACE-QUOTA-NAME [-i MAX-INSTANCE-MEMORY] [-m MEMORY] [-l LOG_RATE] [-n NEW-NAME] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICES] [--allow-paid-service-plans | --disallow-paid-service-plans]
```

Example:
<pre class='terminal'> 
$ cf update-space-quota big -i 20 -m 4096M -l 32K -n bigger -r 20 -s 20 --allow-paid-service-plans
</pre>

### <a name='set-space-quota'></a> Assigning a quota to a space

To assign a quota to a space, run the following command. Replace the placeholder attributes with the values for this quota plan:

```
cf set-space-quota SPACE QUOTA
```

Example:

<pre class='terminal'>
$ cf set-space-quota aSpace big
</pre>

If an error message, such as the following is received you will need to use `cf scale` to update log rate limits 
before the quota can be assigned to the space:

<pre class='terminal'>
$ cf set-space-quota aSpace big
Setting space quota big to space aSpace as admin...
Current usage exceeds new quota values. The space(s) being assigned this quota contain apps running with an unlimited log rate limit.
FAILED

$ cf scale -l 1M example-app
Scaling app example-app in org anOrg / space aSpace as admin...
...

$ cf set-space-quota aSpace big
Setting space quota big to space aSpace as admin...
OK
</pre>

